@phdthesis{Tang1999,
annote = {From Duplicate 1 (Modeling and simulation of the autonomous underwater vehicle, Autolycus - Tang, Sc)

Chapter 1: 
[12]: Humphreys. Complex model which is difficult to implement but highly accurate. 
- Why is it difficult to implement? 
Because it is based off empirically-found vehicle coefficients. 

[18] Nahon: simplified model, however it may be oversimplified when a robust response to a wide range of simulation cases is needed. Coefficients are generic and found from databases of drag coefficients of generic shapes. 

Simplified hydrodynamic model of the vehicle. Nahon [18] uses only body lift and drag forces to model the hydrodynamic characteristics of the vehicle. The lift and drag force coefficients of the vehicle, based on its geometric features, can be found in references such as [10] and [11]. However, an oversimplified hydrodynamic model, as seen in [18], is not likely to produce good results for a wide range of simulation cases.

[6, 7, 8, 12, 18, 19] have simulation references for underwater vehicles. Furthermore, [6, 8, 12] used very complex hydrodynamic models. 

Software in done in Matlab. The dynamic characteristics of the vehicle (such as CG and moments of inertia) are calculated in a spreadsheet, then the hydrodynamic coefficients are estimated, then the simulation is done. 
Pending the simulation results, the design is altered.
The software is based on Nahon's [18] code. 

Chapter 2

Gertler [8]: In 1967 the foundation of submarine motion simulation was laid with the
publication of Standard Equations of Motion for Submarine Simulation by Gertler [8].

Gertler 1967 [8] -{\textgreater} Feldman 1979 [5] 



The simulation model developed by Humphreys [12] adopted a set of linearized equations of motion but maintained a rigorous approach to obtaining the hydrodynamic coefficients. In contrast, the model proposed by Nahon [18] retained the non-linear equations of motion but avoided the rigorous hydrodynamic coefficients by calculating the hydrodynamic forces directly from known relations which govern the flow around simple shapes.

2.2. Experimental Based Model by Humphreys

This model consists of deriving linear, small-perturbation equations of motion for a self-propelled underwater vehicle. 

"The equations include the inertial, hydrodynamic and gravity-buoyancy forces and moments. Assumptions are made to linearize the equations and to decouple the longitudinal motions from the lateral motions. Laplace transformtechniques are applied to obtain the solutions to the equations. The expressions for the transfer functions are given in non-dimensionalized hydrodynamic coefficients."

2.3 Empirical Model by Nahon:
Used "Stability and Control Data Compendium" (aka Datcom) for light and drag coefficients of the AUV. However, these don't account for added mass effects, which can be found in: 
- [20] Newman: added mass terms
- [10] Hoerner: added mass terms
- [11] Hoerner: added mass terms},
author = {Tang, Sc},
file = {:Users/d/Documents/Mendeley Desktop/Tang/1999/tang1999-simulation-autolycus.pdf:pdf},
title = {{Modeling and simulation of the autonomous underwater vehicle, Autolycus}},
url = {http://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/80002},
year = {1999}
}
@article{Siddall2017,
abstract = {{\textcopyright}2016 The Author(s) Published by the Royal Society. All rights reserved. Aerial robots capable of locomotion in both air and water would enable novel mission profiles in complex environments, such as water sampling after floods or underwater structural inspections. The design of such a vehicle is challenging because it implies significant propulsive and structural design trade-offs for operation in both fluids. In this paper, we present a unique Aquatic Micro Air Vehicle (AquaMAV), which uses a reconfigurable wing to dive into the water from flight, inspired by the plunge diving strategy of water diving birds in the family Sulidae. The vehicle's performance is investigated in wind and water tunnel experiments, from which we develop a planar trajectory model. This model is used to predict the dive behaviour of the AquaMAV, and investigate the efficacy of passive dives initiated by wing folding as a means of water entry. The paper also includes first field tests of the AquaMAV prototype where the folding wings are used to initiate a plunge dive.},
