@phdthesis{Nagaoka2011,
annote = {$\backslash$cite{\{}Nagaoka2011{\}} presents two models: one based on skin friction and soil shear, the other based on terramechanics. The skin friction can be modeled simply with the terrain-screw friction coefficients and the screw geometry and allows simulation of the locomotion trajectories. The terramechanics model is more suited towards modeling drawbar pull, and both normal and shear stresses. A third model, called the interaction model, combines these two prior efforts to better model the forces and medium transport. 



The interaction model combines skin friction and soil shear, models the behavior of both the screw and the soil caught in each screw flight, compaction and shear characteristics of the soil, and permits quantitative evaluation of the screw geometry's effect on tractive performance. 

Slip angle experimentations on a custom rig showed that drawbar pull increase significantly when the slip angle, which is the angle of the screw relative to motion of the vehicle, was moved off parallel for a variety of speeds. Furthermore, the drawbar pull displayed increase for positive angles, but decreased with negative slip angle. This would suggest that the more perpendicular the screw angle is relative to vehicle motion, the larger the drawbar pull as the screw side is more perpendicular as well. This would also correlate with other experiments that does a similar comparison but by changing the angle of the blade on the screw itself.

Reference 87 is referenced for online slip prediction method using motor current.

The friction skin friction model considers the friction acting on the screw blade and barrel only in a soft terrain. It can demonstrate, in simulation, longitudinal and lateral locomotion, as well as diagonal strafing, and turning. 

The terramechanics approach models the screw and the entrained soil as one body. This model incorporates locomotion direction and a slip angle. Where the slip angle is the arctan of the velocity in the y and x axis.

What the author denotes as the synthetic interaction model combines the skin friction and terramechanics model to incorporate soil characteristics, such as compaction and shear, and quantify tractive performance as a function of screw geometry. 

Maneuverability tests on sand showed that in cases where the rotational speed was very low, some sideways motion existed. This author posits this is because the angular velocity is not high enough to cause slip between the medium and the barrel drum. In other cases, the speed is fast enough that slip and minimum traction occurs in that direction. 

Achieved manueverability on soft terrain consisted of longitudinal motion, longitudinal steering, and rotational motion.},
author = {Nagaoka, Kenji},
file = {:Users/d/Documents/Mendeley Desktop/Nagaoka/2011/Nagaoka - 2011 - Study on Soil-Screw Interaction of Exploration Robot for Surface and Subsurface Locomotion in Soft Terrain.pdf:pdf},
title = {{Study on Soil-Screw Interaction of Exploration Robot for Surface and Subsurface Locomotion in Soft Terrain}},
year = {2011}
}
